  "prompt": "Is money laundering subject to legal prosecution?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is subject to legal prosecution as it is a criminal offense in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. In China, money laundering is punishable under the **Anti-Money Laundering Law** and the **Criminal Law**. The Chinese government has been actively strengthening its legal framework and enforcement mechanisms to combat money laundering, which is seen as a serious threat to financial order and social stability.\n\nUnder Chinese law, individuals or entities involved in money laundering can face severe penalties, including fines, confiscation of property, and imprisonment. Financial institutions and other organizations are also required to implement strict measures to prevent money laundering, such as customer due diligence, reporting suspicious transactions, and maintaining records.\n\nChina has also been cooperating with international organizations and other countries to combat cross-border money laundering and other financial crimes, demonstrating its commitment to upholding global financial security and the rule of law. If you have any specific questions or need further clarification, feel free to ask!",
